WEBVTT

00:00.994 --> 00:05.740
This Sunday begins another summer in the Psalms for cities church.

00:07.081 --> 00:09.645
And after several years now, we're now more than halfway through the book.

00:09.825 --> 00:17.695
So if you've been with us the last several years, you know that we've now crested that halfway mark as a last summer and we're into the second half of Psalms.

00:17.755 --> 00:23.762
The Psalms are something of the Bible's prayer guide and song book.

00:24.322 --> 00:35.077
You know this, if you're familiar with the Psalms, they teach us in more than 100 shapes and sizes how to sing to God and how to pray.

00:36.178 --> 00:37.080
Not all kinds of things.

00:39.082 --> 00:46.713
They model the inner life of genuine faith, the emotional life of a follower of Christ.

00:47.093 --> 00:53.362
They give us the mountains and the valleys that come with trusting

00:53.954 --> 00:54.875
and following Him.

00:55.155 --> 01:02.183
And we all know, we've followed Him for any amount of time, that there are great mountains and there are great valleys.

01:03.265 --> 01:16.540
So the Psalms are this extraordinary gift in that they help us to see and taste and even begin to feel what true followers of Christ, the people of God, feel by faith.

01:17.801 --> 01:22.066
In Psalm 86, you can hear it in Jodie's reading,

01:22.658 --> 01:25.081
Psalm 86 is a valley song.

01:26.943 --> 01:29.587
It's one of the darker and lonelier songs.

01:29.647 --> 01:31.709
It's a desperate song.

01:32.410 --> 01:35.814
It's not a hopeless song, but it's a desperate one.

01:37.216 --> 01:41.221
It teaches us how to pray when trouble comes.

01:42.483 --> 01:43.444
I think this prayer does.

01:44.625 --> 01:48.450
It teaches us how to pray when trouble comes.

01:49.672 --> 01:51.634
Do you know how to pray

01:52.162 --> 01:53.724
when trouble comes to you.

01:55.666 --> 02:08.463
Not just, Lord, help me or fix this in my life, but do you pray about trouble the way that the Bible prays about trouble?

02:08.483 --> 02:13.389
I know that I don't always pray like Psalm 86 prays about the trouble in my life.

02:14.791 --> 02:20.338
Preparing for this sermon, I was reminded of a prayer that we prayed before meals in our home growing up.

02:21.602 --> 02:28.951
goes, God is great, God is good, and we thank you for this food.

02:30.433 --> 02:30.673
Amen.

02:33.337 --> 02:34.699
I have no idea where the prayer came from.

02:34.739 --> 02:36.501
Maybe my parents made it up, I'm not sure.

02:36.541 --> 02:46.373
And I, even though I've prayed it a thousand times, thousands of times, I'm not entirely sure I understand it.

02:48.937 --> 02:50.098
God is great.

02:50.882 --> 02:56.111
And God is good, isn't great, better than good?

02:56.591 --> 02:58.535
Or is it great and then good?

03:00.698 --> 03:01.580
Maybe it's because it rhymes.

03:01.640 --> 03:07.449
God is great, God is good, and we thank you for this food, good food, almost rhymes.

03:10.314 --> 03:17.586
Whatever it means, wherever it came from, I'm so thankful for those 13 words.

03:19.522 --> 03:27.792
How many children grow up in homes where they never acknowledge that God has anything to do with the food?

03:30.796 --> 03:36.123
How many children grow up in homes where they never hear their parents acknowledge God at all?

03:37.865 --> 03:39.327
Except maybe to use his name in vain.

03:42.491 --> 03:48.178
But I heard PB&J after PB&J, spaghetti,

03:48.450 --> 03:53.958
After spaghetti, I heard, God is great.

03:54.980 --> 03:56.462
God is good.

03:56.522 --> 04:00.628
And it's God who put this food on this table.

04:00.708 --> 04:02.270
And so we thank you, God.

04:03.091 --> 04:03.752
We thank you.

04:06.136 --> 04:10.903
It was a good prayer for a three-year-old, four-year-old, five-year-old soul.

04:13.146 --> 04:15.890
And yet, if you and I were to have lunch this week,

04:17.058 --> 04:18.760
And I still prayed like that.

04:20.282 --> 04:21.905
Something would be off, right?

04:26.431 --> 04:31.918
Hopefully, I've grown some in the ways that I express my thankfulness for spaghetti.

04:33.140 --> 04:34.521
Hopefully, I'm still growing.

04:37.846 --> 04:46.898
I wonder, as I look at Psalm 86, I wonder if some of us are still praying four-year-old prayers about our trials.

04:50.626 --> 05:00.822
We haven't learned how to pray grown-up prayers about the trouble in our lives, and we all have trouble in our lives of various kinds, all of us do.

05:03.746 --> 05:07.151
But we haven't said like the disciples, Lord, teach us to pray.

05:07.191 --> 05:09.795
And that's my prayer for this morning.

05:09.835 --> 05:15.524
Lord, teach us to pray about our trouble, about our trials.

05:17.126 --> 05:19.570
So let me pray that, and then we'll turn to the text.

05:22.818 --> 05:27.846
Father, I mean it when I say we all have trouble in our lives, all of us.

05:29.248 --> 05:36.499
And if we're just coming out of trouble where it's been a little while, trouble's just around the corner.

05:36.619 --> 05:41.406
You promised that to all who follow you in this broken, sinful world.

05:43.469 --> 05:45.412
And we want to know how to come to you.

05:45.733 --> 05:48.838
You open wide your throne of grace in Christ.

05:50.300 --> 05:51.762
You bid us to come.

05:53.346 --> 06:01.176
So I'm asking this morning through your word, through Psalm 86, that you would teach us to pray about the hard things in our lives.

06:01.437 --> 06:02.318
Would you do that now?

06:02.819 --> 06:07.905
Lift up your glory and teach us to pray.

06:07.925 --> 06:10.849
If we pray this in Jesus' name, amen.

06:12.592 --> 06:20.402
All right, before we try and learn from this Psalm, how to pray about our own trouble, we need to ask about the actual trouble that was going on here

06:20.866 --> 06:21.807
for King David.

06:22.088 --> 06:24.831
Why is David crying out to God like this?

06:26.092 --> 06:37.306
We don't know a lot about the circumstances here, and it takes a while in the Psalm before we really learn any of the specific details about his situation, but we do find out what's going on near the end of the Psalm.

06:37.326 --> 06:38.828
We get to learn a little bit anyway.

06:39.969 --> 06:40.871
Look at verse 14.

06:42.412 --> 06:45.737
Oh God, insolent men have risen up against me.

06:46.818 --> 06:50.162
A band of ruthless men seeks my life.

06:51.074 --> 06:53.778
and they do not set you before them.

06:56.121 --> 06:59.886
Now, we have plenty of insolent men in our day.

07:00.326 --> 07:02.269
We just don't typically talk about them that way.

07:03.330 --> 07:10.240
An insolent man is a rude man who is not a respecter of others, especially those in authority in this case of the king.

07:10.260 --> 07:10.860
They're rude.

07:11.742 --> 07:12.883
They're disrespectful.

07:13.344 --> 07:17.009
They're troublemakers who stir up division and hostility.

07:18.230 --> 07:21.074
Again, we have plenty of these in our day.

07:22.082 --> 07:26.589
These particular horrible men are trying to kill the king.

07:27.591 --> 07:29.414
So these are really insolent men.

07:31.076 --> 07:40.091
We don't know who these particular insolent men were, and unfortunately, there were so many men over the course of David's life who tried to kill him that we can't even guess.

07:42.595 --> 07:43.316
Can you imagine?

07:46.361 --> 07:47.282
I don't think

07:47.522 --> 07:57.333
At least those of you that I know well, I don't think any of you have ever gone to bed knowing that someone is driving around looking for you to kill you.

07:59.675 --> 08:01.017
That was normal for David.

08:04.481 --> 08:06.223
He was in serious trouble here.

08:06.423 --> 08:12.850
And while our trouble is different from his, I believe that God means for David's trouble, these insolent men,

08:13.826 --> 08:19.054
I believe he means for his trouble to teach us how to pray in our trouble, whatever trouble that we face.

08:19.815 --> 08:23.120
And I want to summarize the lessons in four simple prayers.

08:23.160 --> 08:25.884
I see all four of these in Psalm 86.

08:25.924 --> 08:26.565
Here are the four.

08:27.286 --> 08:29.249
First, meet my need.

08:31.552 --> 08:34.356
Second, glorify your name.

08:34.376 --> 08:39.324
Third, teach me your way.

08:39.364 --> 08:43.730
And fourth, gladden.

08:44.002 --> 08:44.703
my heart.

08:45.965 --> 08:52.555
Meet my need, glorify your name, teach me your way, gladden my heart.

08:53.016 --> 08:57.203
You should have noticed, grown up prayers, they don't need to be long or complicated.

08:59.026 --> 09:04.074
But I believe there are precious lessons for us in these four simple prayers.

09:04.094 --> 09:06.898
So first, Lord, meet my need.

09:08.354 --> 09:15.301
David doesn't mention the insolent men here in the first verse, but he does start right off by praying about what he needs in the moment, beginning in verse one.

09:15.761 --> 09:21.547
And climb your ear, O Lord, and answer me, for I am poor and needy.

09:22.488 --> 09:26.111
Preserve my life, for I am godly.

09:26.532 --> 09:30.836
Save your servant who trusts in you, you are my God.

09:31.837 --> 09:37.042
Be gracious to me, O Lord, for to you do I cry all the day.

09:39.138 --> 09:45.951
In other words, Lord, meet my immediate need, the need right in front of me right now.

09:47.073 --> 09:55.209
These guys are really trying to kill me, and I'm asking you to stoop down and intervene on my behalf.

09:55.249 --> 09:57.714
Do something about this, God.

09:59.842 --> 10:03.930
I know there are millions of people on earth, now billions in our day.

10:03.951 --> 10:14.653
I know there are millions of people on earth, but I'm asking you to focus your infinite wisdom and strength to protect just one of the millions, me.

10:16.336 --> 10:21.106
And just from a handful of bad men, sort of asking you to do.

10:23.842 --> 10:33.033
When you think about what the Psalms are, these divinely inspired prayer songs meant to be studied, memorized, rehearsed for thousands of years.

10:33.073 --> 10:38.339
We're giving our 45 minutes here to this Psalm 2000 years later, more than 2000 years later.

10:39.100 --> 10:47.890
When you think about what they are, these God-given prayer songs, it's kind of wild how specific some of them are.

10:50.786 --> 10:56.554
God clearly wanted us to hear Godly saints pray for specifics.

10:59.779 --> 11:02.743
It's one of the great gifts of the Psalms and of all the prayers in the Bible.

11:03.144 --> 11:14.620
We get to hear real people pray about real needs, real stuff, like your real stuff.

11:14.640 --> 11:18.866
God knew that we would have our own specifics and he knew full well

11:19.970 --> 11:23.634
that our specifics would be really different from the specifics in Psalm 86.

11:24.394 --> 11:27.838
He's not surprised by any of the specifics in your life.

11:28.858 --> 11:35.385
He knew that we would have our own specifics and he wanted us to know how to pray for specifics.

11:38.047 --> 11:42.712
Do you still pray for the specifics in your life, even the little specifics?

11:44.453 --> 11:49.298
Philippians 4 verse 6 says, do not be anxious about anything

11:49.730 --> 12:00.126
But in everything, by prayer and supplication with thanksgiving, let your request be made known to God.

12:00.146 --> 12:10.342
Anything and everything God wants us to pray for specific needs, large or small, anything and everything.

12:10.362 --> 12:18.034
If you're anxious about something this morning about anything this morning, he wants you to pray about it.

12:20.866 --> 12:31.802
One way God accomplishes his God-sized plans for the world is by addressing you-sized needs in that world.

12:33.625 --> 12:34.306
Do you believe that?

12:34.727 --> 12:47.666
One way that God accomplishes his massive, eternal, God-sized plans for the world, for his glory, is by meeting you-sized needs.

12:49.890 --> 12:53.575
Month by month, week by week, even hour by hour.

12:54.736 --> 12:56.799
Lord, meet my need.

12:59.423 --> 13:00.884
Okay, so the first prayer, meet my need.

13:00.925 --> 13:02.707
It's a real and it's a good prayer.

13:02.767 --> 13:13.721
We pray for specifics as Christians, like when madmen are trying to kill us, just happening here, or when the youngest child's eyes start swelling a little bit and you're not quite sure why.

13:13.761 --> 13:17.266
We pray for specific needs.

13:19.810 --> 13:24.375
David really wants God to intervene in his actual human life and change something.

13:24.595 --> 13:27.978
Meet my need, O God.

13:27.998 --> 13:30.381
But that's not the highest prayer in Psalm 86.

13:30.401 --> 13:34.004
And this is where our prayers start to grow up into fuller maturity.

13:34.024 --> 13:35.146
Let's start in verse six.

13:36.827 --> 13:38.889
Give ear, O Lord, to my prayer.

13:40.031 --> 13:42.153
Listen to my plea for grace.

13:43.254 --> 13:46.697
In the day of my trouble, I call upon you for you.

13:46.837 --> 13:47.378
Answer me.

13:49.602 --> 13:51.024
He's still asking for help here.

13:51.645 --> 13:54.269
Give ear to my prayer, meet my specific need.

13:55.511 --> 13:56.653
What does he say next?

13:57.454 --> 13:58.596
This is the second prayer.

13:58.656 --> 14:00.519
Glorify your name.

14:01.801 --> 14:03.904
Glorify your name.

14:03.924 --> 14:05.627
Here's how David prays it, verse eight.

14:07.129 --> 14:10.034
There is none like you among the gods, oh Lord.

14:10.466 --> 14:12.990
Nor are there any works like yours.

14:13.511 --> 14:21.002
All the nations you have made shall come and worship before you, O Lord, and shall glorify your name.

14:21.803 --> 14:25.229
For you are great and do wondrous things.

14:25.549 --> 14:30.817
You alone are God."

14:30.837 --> 14:32.019
Why would he pray like that?

14:35.965 --> 14:39.250
Lord, I need you to protect me from these bad guys.

14:39.426 --> 14:42.589
They're trying to kill me, and I need you to stop them.

14:42.629 --> 14:45.352
There is none like you among the gods, O Lord.

14:46.233 --> 14:47.514
Nor are there any works like yours.

14:47.674 --> 14:52.640
All the nations you have made shall come and worship before you, O Lord, and shall glorify your name.

14:52.780 --> 14:54.021
Why does he pray like that?

14:57.224 --> 15:06.834
Why would he suddenly go from this particular need, the specific need, to the promise that all the nations are gonna bow and worship God?

15:08.386 --> 15:14.396
glorify your name, oh God, the Bible talks like this so much that you hear it and you don't even blink.

15:17.882 --> 15:18.964
Why does he pray like that?

15:21.769 --> 15:34.130
David prays like this because our confidence in asking God to do anything in our lives is rooted in his commitment to do all things for his glory.

15:36.450 --> 15:47.944
Our confidence that he'll do anything in our lives is rooted in his commitment to do all things, everything that he does for his glory.

15:49.526 --> 15:51.989
God will glorify his name.

15:52.089 --> 15:54.552
We see this all throughout the Bible from beginning to end.

15:54.652 --> 15:59.238
And amazingly, it's hard to even believe it.

15:59.338 --> 16:05.746
Amazingly, he chooses to glorify himself through showing kindness to us.

16:07.810 --> 16:09.332
by meeting our needs.

16:12.236 --> 16:32.786
He pours grace on undeserving people like me, grace to forgive me and save me from hell, grace to change me and empower me to live more like him, and then grace to meet my very practical needs, like daily bread.

16:36.098 --> 16:40.825
to provide the food that I need and the home that I need and the job that I need.

16:41.807 --> 16:49.819
God spreads his glory by loving his needy people who trust him and depend on him for everything.

16:52.723 --> 16:57.310
And so we don't just pray, God deliver me from the insolent men because you like to help people.

16:57.951 --> 16:58.432
He does.

17:00.275 --> 17:05.042
No, we pray like David, meet my need because meeting my need

17:05.154 --> 17:29.938
will show the world what kind of God you are, that you are gracious and merciful, slow to anger and abounding rich in steadfast love, that you never abandon your children, that you own everything in the universe and you will spend your infinite riches to care for us.

17:32.258 --> 17:41.329
that you have the power and authority to heal any illness and to mend any relationship no matter how helpless it seems you can do it.

17:41.369 --> 17:48.377
How glorious will you look, oh God, if you do this?

17:50.119 --> 17:54.143
God glorify your name through my need.

17:57.347 --> 17:59.890
This prayer for God to glorify his name

18:00.770 --> 18:04.594
Among all the nations, it serves at least two great purposes for us, though, in trouble.

18:05.835 --> 18:08.377
First, it grounds our hope that he might actually do something.

18:08.417 --> 18:11.660
He loves to glorify his name, and he glorifies his name by loving us.

18:13.182 --> 18:17.246
He'll care for us because that's how he reveals his glory to the world.

18:17.286 --> 18:21.389
But second, a prayer like this, glorify your name.

18:22.450 --> 18:30.418
It widens our eyes beyond our immediate need or heartache to remember who God is

18:31.842 --> 18:33.364
and what he's doing in the world.

18:35.727 --> 18:39.572
The nations you have made shall come and worship before you.

18:39.932 --> 18:42.636
That's going to happen no question.

18:43.637 --> 18:45.679
You're doing that, O God, right now.

18:48.723 --> 18:54.130
It's going to happen no matter what happens in my little circumstances here, in my trouble.

18:55.232 --> 19:00.338
And when that happens, when all the nations bow and glorify you,

19:01.282 --> 19:09.735
all my little or big circumstances, they're gonna be made right, fully right forever.

19:13.560 --> 19:20.090
Praying glorify your name, it gets us out of the rut of only praying about our needs.

19:22.433 --> 19:24.156
You've probably been here, I know I've been.

19:24.196 --> 19:31.026
Our prayer lives can become almost all about the job, the job, the job,

19:32.162 --> 19:42.019
The spouse, the spouse, the spouse, the child, the child, the child, the injury, or sickness, or weakness, or conflict.

19:42.420 --> 19:47.949
Praying like David prays here, it lifts us out of our need to see a bigger picture.

19:49.151 --> 19:52.517
God is glorifying His name all over the world.

19:52.637 --> 19:57.586
And one day soon, all the nations are going to see Him and worship.

19:59.970 --> 20:06.176
Lord, hallowed be your name, your kingdom come, your will be done.

20:06.216 --> 20:12.723
Then give us this day, your daily breath.

20:12.743 --> 20:15.926
It doesn't mean that we don't pray, meet my needs, prayers.

20:16.006 --> 20:16.947
David's doing that here.

20:17.027 --> 20:19.810
I'm encouraging you to do that with your specifics.

20:20.430 --> 20:28.178
But it does put our meet my needs, prayers, into a wider, fuller, more glorious perspective.

20:29.794 --> 20:33.440
God, meet my need for your glory.

20:35.243 --> 20:36.905
Those aren't the only two prayers in this Psalm though.

20:36.925 --> 20:48.063
When trouble comes to David, he prays, meet my need, glorify your name, and then third verse 11, teach me your way.

20:49.425 --> 20:54.232
Teach me your way, O Lord, that I may walk in your truth.

20:54.873 --> 20:57.938
Unite my heart to fear your name.

20:59.554 --> 21:06.786
Let this trouble, this trial, let it be an opportunity for you to make me more holy.

21:09.610 --> 21:22.932
To refine away more of the remaining sin in my life, more than peace or relief from the trouble, I want that, but more than peace and relief from the trouble, I want greater godliness.

21:24.775 --> 21:26.738
I want to be more like you, oh God.

21:28.514 --> 21:34.841
Notice, he says, verse two, when he prays, he says, preserve my life from these men, for I am godly.

21:36.763 --> 21:42.329
I take that to mean he doesn't think that God is mainly confronting him with this trouble.

21:44.351 --> 21:45.632
We see that in other Psalms.

21:47.114 --> 21:50.878
But here he says, answer my prayer for I am godly.

21:51.418 --> 21:55.122
I'm trying to do the right thing in this awful circumstance.

21:55.490 --> 22:08.370
He doesn't think that God's using this trouble to confront him, but even though he believes that he's doing the right things in this case, even though he believes he's right, he wants to be even more like God.

22:08.390 --> 22:10.733
That's his hunger with this prayer.

22:11.074 --> 22:14.279
God, use this trouble to sanctify me.

22:15.881 --> 22:19.487
Teach me your way, O God.

22:19.507 --> 22:20.468
This is James 1.

22:20.969 --> 22:24.114
Count it all joy, my brothers,

22:24.642 --> 22:33.050
When you meet trials of various kinds, trials come, count it joy, not just good, but joy.

22:34.452 --> 22:34.732
Why?

22:35.012 --> 22:50.067
For you know that the testing of your faith produces steadfastness, and let steadfastness have its full effect that you may be perfect and complete, lacking in nothing.

22:52.209 --> 22:53.330
Trial comes.

22:54.210 --> 22:55.552
Lord, teach me your way.

22:58.015 --> 23:03.662
Give me what I need to be more like you, perfect and complete, lacking in nothing.

23:05.104 --> 23:08.609
And don't just teach me to do certain things and to avoid others.

23:09.370 --> 23:10.852
No, this prayer is much bolder than that.

23:10.892 --> 23:11.733
I wonder if you caught it.

23:11.853 --> 23:12.654
Again, verse 11.

23:12.974 --> 23:22.066
Teach me your way, O Lord, that I may walk in your truth, unite my heart to fear your name.

23:24.546 --> 23:28.291
I don't want you to just help me do the right things and not the bad things.

23:29.853 --> 23:32.817
I want you to change me somewhere deeper than my doing.

23:35.540 --> 23:36.982
I want you to change me in here.

23:37.002 --> 23:41.247
I want you to unite my heart toward you.

23:41.267 --> 23:51.480
I feel how distracted and divided my heart can be and I want my whole heart to be united and aligned and hungry for you.

23:51.641 --> 23:52.722
That's what I want, God.

23:53.026 --> 23:56.471
unite my heart to fear your name.

23:56.931 --> 24:06.665
And I know that you often change me for the better in here through something hard out there.

24:12.153 --> 24:13.695
Do you think that way when trouble comes?

24:16.779 --> 24:18.802
You get bad news of some kind.

24:19.778 --> 24:23.083
You feel hostility and opposition of some kind.

24:23.503 --> 24:30.673
Do you think, oh, God's about to make me more like Him?

24:35.780 --> 24:36.962
I know I don't always think that way.

24:38.324 --> 24:39.866
I think I don't like this.

24:41.649 --> 24:42.570
God, why this?

24:43.892 --> 24:44.372
Why now?

24:44.473 --> 24:45.494
Why for this long?

24:47.176 --> 24:48.338
It's how I often respond.

24:49.538 --> 24:53.502
I've talked before about a bad leak that we had in our kitchen late last summer.

24:55.404 --> 24:56.365
Well, I'm still talking about it.

24:58.747 --> 24:59.909
That trial isn't over yet.

25:01.150 --> 25:02.311
It's more than nine months later.

25:02.331 --> 25:07.396
I won't get into all of it, but it's been a real trial.

25:07.456 --> 25:17.106
I call it a small tea trial because we are praying for some of you who are bearing going through far worse, far, far worse.

25:18.466 --> 25:19.367
But it's been a trial.

25:19.567 --> 25:24.893
And in my low moments, I have not had a Psalm 86 heart about it.

25:24.994 --> 25:29.919
I've had a, can't this just be over attitude about it?

